When we want to move electrons through a circuit, a potential difference is needed in
order to make them do so. This potential difference is called voltage. Voltage is measured
in volts, whereas current is measured in amperes, or amps.
Voltage creates the “pressure” necessary in order for electrons to flow. Imagine water
being pumped through a pipe. The water flowing through the pipe is analogous to a
current of electrons, whereas the pump can be likened to voltage. The harder the water
gets pumped, the more quickly the water will flow through.

7. Take the four AA batteries and insert them
into the battery pack. Then connect the red
wire on your battery pack to the positive
(red) power rail, and the black one to the
negative (red) rail, also known as ground.
The circuit must be a closed one; in other words, the wires connecting the two terminals must form a
complete loop. If they don’t, it is known as an “open circuit,” and the current cannot flow from one
end of the battery to the other.
This is what happens when you flip a light switch. When you flip the switch on, the circuit closes,
and current can flow, thus lighting up the filament in the bulb. Contrariwise, when the switch stays
open, current does not reach the positive terminal, and the bulb remains unlit.
